Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Instance 1: Constructs Involved: Take Vocabulary Quiz, Load Quiz Questions, Take Vocabulary Quiz --include--> Load Quiz Questions
   Instance 1: Explanation: "Load Quiz Questions" is an inclusion use case included only by "Take Vocabulary Quiz." It is not associated with any actor, is not included by any other use case, does not include or extend any use case, is not extended by any use case, and is not involved in any generalization. "Load Quiz Questions" does not represent a complete service observable to any user — it is merely a functional step decomposed out of the quiz-taking process. This constitutes the Functional Decomposition antipattern.

   Instance 2: Constructs Involved: Complete Lesson, Update Progress Tracker, Complete Lesson --include--> Update Progress Tracker
   Instance 2: Explanation: "Update Progress Tracker" is an inclusion use case included only by "Complete Lesson." It has no direct actor association, is not included by any other use case, does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any use case, and is not a generalization or specialization. Updating the progress tracker is an internal system step, not a standalone service delivering an observable result to a user. This is a clear instance of Functional Decomposition.

   Instance 3: Constructs Involved: Practice Pronunciation, Record Audio Input, Practice Pronunciation --include--> Record Audio Input
   Instance 3: Explanation: "Record Audio Input" is an inclusion use case included only by "Practice Pronunciation." It is not associated with any actor, not included by any other use case, does not include or extend any use case, is not extended, and is not part of any generalization hierarchy. Recording audio is a sub-step of practicing pronunciation, not a complete service on its own. This represents functional decomposition of "Practice Pronunciation" into an unnecessary inclusion.
